## Phase 0 – First 3–6 Months: Accept Reality & Build Foundation

This is the most important phase — because 70–80% of students waste it.

### 1. Accept the Truth (Do This First Week)
Write down honestly (in a note or phone):  
- What do I actually like doing? (gaming, teaching, drawing, talking, fixing things, numbers, stories, science…)  
- What am I naturally good at? (logic, communication, creativity, memory, hands-on work…)  
- What do I hate? (sitting long hours, math, public speaking, pressure…)  
- What do my parents expect? (govt job, IT, doctor, MBA…)  
- What do I want money for? (freedom, family, travel, car, house…)  
- What lifestyle do I want in 2030? (9–5, remote, startup stress, travel job, own business…)  

No right or wrong answer — just be brutally honest.

### 2. Understand the Real Game in 2026–2030 India
- 15–20 lakh engineering students graduate every year  
- Only ~10–20% get decent private jobs (above 8–12 LPA)  
- Top 5% get product companies / high CTC (20–60+ LPA)  
- Top 1% get FAANG-level / unicorn / abroad (50–150+ LPA)  
- Rest → mass recruiters (TCS, Infosys, Wipro 3.5–7 LPA), non-IT, unemployed, or higher studies  

The game is not "study hard" anymore.  
The game is:  
- Skill depth (coding / AI / cloud / design / communication)  
- Proof (projects, GitHub, internship, Kaggle, LeetCode rating)  
- Visibility (LinkedIn, referrals, content, network)  
- Consistency over 3–4 years  

### 3. First 90 Days Action Plan (Do This No Matter What Branch)
Week 1–2: Setup & Clarity  
- Make GitHub + LinkedIn (professional photo, headline: "B.Tech [Branch] '29 | Exploring [Coding / AI / Core]")  
- Install VS Code + Python + Git  
- Create one Google Sheet: Weekly Tracker (hours coded, problems solved, projects, applications, mood)  
- Talk to 2–3 seniors (honest conversation — what worked, what they regret)  

Week 3–6: Learn One Skill Deeply (Choose ONE)  
Option A – Want software job fast → Python + DSA  
Option B – Interested in AI/ML/Data → Python + Pandas + first ML  
Option C – Core branch lover → branch subjects + C/C++/MATLAB  
Option D – Not sure → Python (it opens all doors)  

Week 7–12: First Project + GitHub  
- Build 1–2 small projects (to-do list, quiz game, expense tracker)  
- Push to GitHub with clean README  
- Post on LinkedIn: "Built my first project! Link in comments"  

### 4. Decide Your Direction (By End of First Year)
Do not decide forever — just pick one direction for 12–18 months.

Direction 1 – Software Development / SDE (highest jobs)  
- Python → DSA → Full-stack / Backend / Frontend  
- Target: 15–40 LPA product/startup  

Direction 2 – AI/ML / Data Science (hot & growing)  
- Python → Maths (stats/linear algebra) → ML → Deep Learning  
- Target: 12–45+ LPA AI roles  

Direction 3 – Core Branch (Mechanical/Civil/Electrical)  
- Branch subjects + software skills (Python/MATLAB)  
- Target: core companies + IT switch  

Direction 4 – Non-Tech (MBA, Govt, UPSC, Entrepreneurship)  
- Good CGPA + communication + extracurriculars  

You can change direction later — but pick one for now.

Phase 2 – Second Year: Skill Explosion & First Internship

1. Choose One Primary Skill Stack  
Stack A – Software Engineer Path  
- DSA (Striver SDE Sheet medium)  
- Full-stack (MERN / Java Spring)  
- Cloud basics (AWS free tier)  

Stack B – AI/ML Engineer Path  
- DSA medium  
- Maths (stats, linear algebra, probability – Khan Academy)  
- ML (scikit-learn, XGBoost)  
- DL (PyTorch / TensorFlow + Hugging Face)  

Stack C – Hybrid (Most Safe)  
- DSA medium  
- Python + Full-stack basics  
- ML basics (scikit-learn + one DL project)  

2. Project Strategy (Do 8–15 Projects)  
Rule: Every project must be deployed + GitHub + LinkedIn post  

Easy Projects (First 6 months)  
- To-Do / Task Manager (React or Python Flask)  
- Personal Blog (Markdown + Streamlit)  
- Expense Tracker with charts  
- Quiz / Learning App  

Medium Projects (Next 6 months)  
- E-commerce mini (products, cart, fake payment)  
- Movie Recommender (simple ML)  
- Sentiment Analyzer (text)  
- House Price Predictor (deployed)  

Advanced Projects (Second Year End)  
- Chatbot with LLM (Hugging Face)  
- Image Classifier (CNN)  
- Recommendation System  
- End-to-End ML Pipeline  

3. Internship Strategy (Start Applying Mid-Second Year)  
- Platforms: Internshala, LinkedIn, AngelList/Wellfound, startup careers page  
- Apply 50–100 times — even if "not ready"  
- Resume: 1 page — projects links + DSA count + GitHub  
- Target: 1 internship summer 2027 (even unpaid/remote = huge)  

Phase 3 – Third Year: Mastery & Serious Placements

1. Advanced Skills  
- DSA hard (company tagged)  
- System Design basics (LLD + HLD intro)  
- Cloud (AWS/GCP free tier)  
- AI/ML advanced (transformers, RAG, agents)  

2. Placement Preparation  
- LeetCode medium-hard (company lists)  
- Mock interviews (Pramp, Interviewing.io, friends)  
- Behavioral stories (STAR method)  
- LinkedIn outreach (50+ messages/month)  

3. Final Year Strategy  
- On-campus + off-campus both  
- Referrals from seniors/alumni/internship managers  
- Multiple offers — choose best fit  

Phase 4 – After Graduation (2030 & Beyond)

1. First Job Strategy  
- Join good company even if lower pay (learning > money first 2 years)  
- Switch after 1.5–2 years (biggest jump)  

2. Long-Term Options  
- Stay in tech → senior engineer / staff / architect  
- AI/ML specialization → research / startup / abroad  
- MBA / higher studies  
- Entrepreneurship / freelancing  
- Govt / PSU (if interested)  

Common Traps & How to Avoid Them  
- Trap 1: "Everyone is doing coding" — do what you like  
- Trap 2: "I need 9+ CGPA" — 7.5+ + skills > 9+ no skills  
- Trap 3: "I will start after exams" — start 30 min today  
- Trap 4: "I need perfect plan" — start messy, improve later  
- Trap 5: Burnout — rest is part of the plan  

